  "prompt": "English Grammar: Which is more Grammatically Correct - \"I wish I was there\" OR \"I wish I were there\"?",
  "response": "The grammatically correct form is \"I wish I were there.\" This is an example of the subjunctive mood, which is used to express hypothetical or unreal situations. In this case, \"were\" is used instead of \"was\" to indicate that the situation is not true (you are not actually there). Using \"were\" in this context maintains the traditional rules of English grammar.",
